                <div class="description">
                    <p>The Great Gatsby by F. Scott Fitzgerald is a classic American novel set in the Roaring Twenties, a period of wealth, excess, and social change in the United States. Published in 1925, the novel explores themes of love, ambition, the American Dream, and the moral decay hidden beneath the glitz and glamour of high society.

The story is narrated by Nick Carraway, a Yale graduate and World War I veteran who moves to West Egg, Long Island, to pursue a career in bonds. He soon becomes fascinated by his mysterious and wealthy neighbor, Jay Gatsby, a self-made millionaire known for his extravagant parties. However, Gatsby?s wealth is not simply for show?it is a means to an end. He is desperately trying to win back Daisy Buchanan, his lost love, who is now married to the wealthy but unfaithful Tom Buchanan. Gatsby and Daisy were once deeply in love, but their relationship was torn apart by social class differences and the expectations of old-money aristocracy.

As the novel progresses, Gatsby and Daisy rekindle their romance, but their love is doomed from the start. Tom exposes Gatsby?s questionable wealth, hinting at illegal activities such as bootlegging. In a tragic turn of events, Daisy accidentally kills Myrtle Wilson, Tom?s mistress, in a hit-and-run accident, but Gatsby takes the blame to protect her. In the end, Gatsby is shot and killed by Myrtle?s grieving husband, who believes Gatsby was responsible for her death. Shockingly, no one from Gatsby?s glamorous social circle attends his funeral, highlighting the emptiness of the world he so desperately wanted to be a part of.

The Great Gatsby is a poignant critique of the American Dream, showing how the pursuit of wealth and status often leads to disappointment and destruction. Fitzgerald?s novel remains a timeless reflection on love, greed, and the illusion of happiness, making it one of the greatest works of American literature.</p>
                    
